{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774408992,"nonce":"XAdLlbaUY95URsYjNgw0MKBY6yM=","title":"Control cost ratio sweep: find optimal balance for SISU-conditional behavior","message":"Current experiments used target_ratio 0.3 and 0.5. The nn_output weight converged to only 3-4× initial (1e-5 → 3-4e-5). A wider sweep (0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9) at pert_std=1 and pert_std=10 might find a sweet spot where being 'too robust' at SISU=0 is costly enough to force strategy switching.\n\nThe hypothesis: there exists a target_ratio where the adaptive control cost penalty is large enough to give the network real speed headroom, while not so large that the network simply refuses to move. In that regime, SISU-conditional velocity modulation becomes the optimal policy because using high forces at SISU=1 (low uncertainty) is cheap but using high forces at SISU=0 (high uncertainty) is costly.\n\nCurrent evidence: at ratio=0.3-0.5, SISU→velocity effect remains \u003c1% across all tested conditions. At ratio=0.3 APT+update pert_std=1, a tentative +3.4% effect appeared but was accompanied by anomalously low overall velocity (2.156 vs ~2.4 elsewhere), suggesting convergence artifact rather than genuine SISU-conditional strategy.\n\nCross-ref: Bug: 3b70482, Bug: 61d3502.","files":null}]}